  <subsection>
    <title>Introduction:</title>
    <p>
      In this activity,
      you will be using the assignment operator <c>:=</c>,
      which allows you assign Maple output to a name of your choice.
      This is especially useful for assigning expressions and functions on one Maple input,
      before manipulating those expressions later on in your worksheet.
    </p>
  </subsection>
  <subsection>
    <title>Exercises:</title>
    <ol>
      <li>
        <p>
          Assign the expression <m>\dfrac{\sin(x)+3}{\cos(x)+1}</m> to <c>expr</c> and then use the <c>subs()</c> command to substitute <m>x=3</m> into <c>expr</c>.
          Evaluate this as a decimal with <m>15</m> digits.
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          Assign the expression <m>x^2+2^x</m> to <c>expr2</c> and substitute <m>y =</m><nbsp/><c>expr2</c> into the expression <m>y^2+3y</m>.
          <aside>
            <p>
              Instead of using the <c>subs</c> command multiple times,
              it is often a better practice to define a function and use function notation instead.
            </p>
          </aside>
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          Assign the expression <m>2x^2-4x+7</m> to <c>poly</c> and then substitute <m>x=5+h</m> into <c>poly</c> and simplify.
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          Consider the function <m>f(x) = (1-x^2) { e}^{-\sfrac{x^2}{2}}</m>.
          <aside>
            <p>
              The exponential function, <m>{ e}^x</m>,
              in Maple is denoted as <c>exp(x)</c>.
            </p>
          </aside>
            <idx><h>mathematical functions</h><h>exponential</h></idx>
          <ol>
            <li>
              <p>
                Assign the function to <m>f(x)</m>.
                <aside>
                  <p>
                    When assigning the function to <m>f(x)</m>,
                    use the <m>:=</m> operator.
                  </p>
                </aside>
            <idx><h>assignment operator</h></idx>
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                This function <m>f(x)</m> is known as the
                <em>Mexican Hat Function</em>.
                Can you see why?
                Plot the graph of <m>f(x)</m>.
              </p>
            </li>
          </ol>
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          Maple, by default, does not know the function
          <aside>
            <p>
              Often, this function is denoted as
              <m>{ sinc}_\pi(x)</m> and <m>{ sinc}(x) = \frac{\sin (x)}{x}</m>.
            </p>
          </aside>
          <me>
            sinc(x) = \dfrac{\sin(\pi x)}{\pi x}
          </me>,
          which is important in engineering.
          <aside>
            <p>
              Be sure to include a multiplication symbol or space between <m>\pi</m> and <m>x</m>.
            </p>
          </aside>
            <idx><h>Pi</h></idx>
          <aside>
            <p>
              The mathematical constant <m>\pi = 3.14\cdots</m> must be typed into Maple as <c>Pi</c>.
            </p>
          </aside>
            <idx><h>Pi</h></idx>
          <ol>
            <li>
              <p>
                Assign this function to <m>sinc(x)</m>.
                <aside>
                  <p>
                    When assigning the function to <m>sinc(x)</m>,
                    use the <m>:=</m> operator.
                  </p>
                </aside>
            <idx><h>assignment operator</h></idx>
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                Evaluate <m>sinc(3)</m>,
                <m>sinc\left(\frac{1}{2}\right)</m>, and <m>sinc(0.25)</m>.
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                Plot the graph of <m>sinc(x)</m>.
              </p>
            </li>
          </ol>
        </p>
      </li>
    </ol>
  </subsection>
</section>